Note:
==============================================================================
CURVE_P256 - NIST P-256 short Weierstrass curve operations (FIPS 186-4 D.1.2.3)
==============================================================================

Implements the NIST P-256 elliptic curve over Fp256:

    y^2 = x^3 + a*x + b  (mod p)
    a = -3  (i.e. p - 3 in canonical form)
    b = 5ac635d8 aa3a93e7 b3ebbd55 769886bc 651d06b0 cc53b0f6 3bce3c3e 27d2604b

The base point G has order n with cofactor h = 1:

    Gx = 6b17d1f2 e12c4247 f8bce6e5 63a440f2 77037d81 2deb33a0 f4a13945 d898c296
    Gy = 4fe342e2 fe1a7f9b 8ee7eb4a 7c0f9e16 2bce3357 6b315ece cbb64068 37bf51f5
    n  = ffffffff 00000000 ffffffff ffffffff bce6faad a7179e84 f3b9cac2 fc632551

Internal coordinate system: Jacobian projective (X : Y : Z) representing the
affine point (X/Z^2, Y/Z^3) when Z != 0. The point at infinity is encoded as
Z = 0. Point arithmetic uses the Bernstein-Lange formulas which are complete
for a = -3 curves (no exceptional cases for distinct points), and a separate
specialized doubling formula. Final outputs are converted to affine for
serialization.

Scalar multiplication uses a constant-time double-and-add ladder. For each
scalar bit from MSB to LSB we double the accumulator and conditionally add
the base point. The conditional add is implemented branchlessly via a
constant-time point select that walks both candidate points regardless of the
bit value. This eliminates timing-based scalar leakage at the cost of always
performing the addition (overhead constant per bit).

Memory: every per-call temporary is allocated from an arena supplied by the
caller. A single scalar multiplication on P-256 issues roughly 1000 arena
allocations of ~120 bytes each plus the BigInt scratch space; budget at
least 1 MiB of arena per signing operation to stay comfortably above the
peak.

Point encoding (SEC 1 v2.0 sections 2.3.3 / 2.3.4):
    0x00                : point at infinity         (1  byte)
    0x02 || X           : compressed, y is even     (33 bytes)
    0x03 || X           : compressed, y is odd      (33 bytes)
    0x04 || X || Y      : uncompressed              (65 bytes)
    0x06 || X || Y      : hybrid, y is even         (65 bytes)
    0x07 || X || Y      : hybrid, y is odd          (65 bytes)

References:
- NIST FIPS 186-4 Appendix D.1.2.3 (curve P-256 / P-256 parameters).
- SEC 1: Elliptic Curve Cryptography v2.0, section 2.3 (point representations).
- SEC 2 v2.0 section 2.4.2 (secp256r1).
- Bernstein, Lange "Faster addition and doubling on elliptic curves" (2007).
- Hankerson, Menezes, Vanstone "Guide to Elliptic Curve Cryptography",
  Chapters 3 (point arithmetic) and 4 (scalar multiplication).
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory
Import "runtime/core/memory/arena.runa" as Arena
Import "compiler/frontend/import_system/crypto/bigint.runa" as BigInt
Import "compiler/frontend/import_system/crypto/bigint_extra.runa" as BigIntX
Import "compiler/frontend/import_system/crypto/field_p256.runa" as Field

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Constants
Note: ============================================================================

Constant CURVE_P256_BYTES as Integer is 32
Constant CURVE_P256_LIMBS as Integer is 4
Constant CURVE_P256_POINT_BYTES as Integer is 65
Constant CURVE_P256_COMPRESSED_BYTES as Integer is 33
Constant CURVE_P256_JACOBIAN_STRUCT_BYTES as Integer is 24

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Curve parameter loaders
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "curve_p256_b" takes arena as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the curve coefficient b for the short Weierstrass equation
    y^2 = x^3 - 3x + b. Value per FIPS 186-4 D.1.2.3:
    5ac635d8 aa3a93e7 b3ebbd55 769886bc 651d06b0 cc53b0f6 3bce3c3e 27d2604b.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Allocate a 10-limb BigInt and populate four little-endian 64-bit limbs.
    Limb 0 is the low 64 bits (3bce3c3e27d2604b), limb 3 the top
    (5ac635d8aa3a93e7).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Single arena allocation plus six writes. Public constant.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Returns public curve parameter. No side-channel concerns.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let b be proc bigint_alloc from BigInt with arena, 10
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with b, 0, 4309448131093880907
    proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with b, 1, 7285987128567378166
    proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with b, 2, 12964664127075681980
    proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with b, 3, 6540974713487397863
    proc bigint_set_limb_count from BigInt with b, 4
    Return b
End Process

Process called "curve_p256_order" takes arena as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the order n of the base point G. Per FIPS 186-4 D.1.2.3:
    ffffffff 00000000 ffffffff ffffffff bce6faad a7179e84 f3b9cac2 fc632551.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Allocate 10-limb BigInt and populate four limbs little-endian.
    Limb 0 = f3b9cac2fc632551, Limb 1 = bce6faada7179e84,
    Limb 2 = ffffffffffffffff, Limb 3 = ffffffff00000000.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Single arena allocation. Public constant.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Returns public curve parameter.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let n be proc bigint_alloc from BigInt with arena, 10
    If n is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with n, 0, 17562291160714782033
    proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with n, 1, 13611842547513532036
    proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with n, 2, 18446744073709551615
    proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with n, 3, 18446744069414584320
    proc bigint_set_limb_count from BigInt with n, 4
    Return n
End Process

Process called "curve_p256_gx" takes arena as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the x-coordinate of the base point G. Per FIPS 186-4 D.1.2.3:
    6b17d1f2 e12c4247 f8bce6e5 63a440f2 77037d81 2deb33a0 f4a13945 d898c296.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Allocate 10-limb BigInt and populate four limbs.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Single arena allocation. Public constant.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Returns public curve parameter.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let gx be proc bigint_alloc from BigInt with arena, 10
    If gx is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with gx, 0, 17627433388654248598
    proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with gx, 1, 8575836109218198432
    proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with gx, 2, 17923454489921339634
    proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with gx, 3, 7716867327612699207
    proc bigint_set_limb_count from BigInt with gx, 4
    Return gx
End Process

Process called "curve_p256_gy" takes arena as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the y-coordinate of the base point G. Per FIPS 186-4 D.1.2.3:
    4fe342e2 fe1a7f9b 8ee7eb4a 7c0f9e16 2bce3357 6b315ece cbb64068 37bf51f5.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Allocate 10-limb BigInt and populate four limbs.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Single arena allocation. Public constant.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Returns public curve parameter.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let gy be proc bigint_alloc from BigInt with arena, 10
    If gy is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with gy, 0, 14678990851816772085
    proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with gy, 1, 3156516839386865358
    proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with gy, 2, 10297457778147434006
    proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with gy, 3, 5756518291402817435
    proc bigint_set_limb_count from BigInt with gy, 4
    Return gy
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Point construction and field access
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "curve_p256_point_alloc" takes arena as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Allocates a Jacobian point struct (24 bytes holding three BigInt
    pointers) and initializes all three component BigInts to zero with
    enough capacity for multiplication results.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. arena_allocate 24 bytes for the struct header.
    2. For X, Y, Z allocate fresh BigInts via field_p256_zero (10-limb).
    3. Write three pointers into the struct at offsets 0, 8, 16.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Four arena allocations totalling 24 + 3*96 = 312 bytes.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No side-channel concerns; allocation only.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let pt be proc arena_allocate from Arena with arena, CURVE_P256_JACOBIAN_STRUCT_BYTES
    If pt is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let x be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    If x is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let y be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    If y is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let z be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    If z is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_qword from Memory with pt, 0, x
    proc memory_set_qword from Memory with pt, 8, y
    proc memory_set_qword from Memory with pt, 16, z
    Return pt
End Process

Process called "curve_p256_point_x" takes pt as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the X-coordinate BigInt pointer of a Jacobian point.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Reads pointer at offset 0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Single memory load.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No side-channel; pure accessor.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc memory_get_qword from Memory with pt, 0
End Process

Process called "curve_p256_point_y" takes pt as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the Y-coordinate BigInt pointer.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Reads pointer at offset 8.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Single memory load.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No side-channel.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc memory_get_qword from Memory with pt, 8
End Process

Process called "curve_p256_point_z" takes pt as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the Z-coordinate BigInt pointer.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Reads pointer at offset 16.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Single memory load.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No side-channel.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc memory_get_qword from Memory with pt, 16
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Helper: copy one P-256 field element into a destination BigInt buffer
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "curve_p256_field_copy_into" takes dest as Integer, src as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Copies the value of src into the pre-allocated dest BigInt buffer
    so both refer to the same numerical value with src's limb count.
    Used by curve operations that mutate the destination's limbs
    without re-allocating.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Read src limb count.
    2. Zero dest's full capacity (drop any prior value).
    3. Copy limbs one by one.
    4. Set dest limb count.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(limb_count) writes; for P-256 elements at most 4 active limbs
    are copied plus zeroing of any remaining capacity.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant time over dest's capacity which is fixed at allocation;
    does not branch on values.
    @End Security_Scope

    If dest is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If src is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let dest_cap be proc bigint_get_limb_capacity from BigInt with dest
    Let zi be 0
    While zi is less than dest_cap:
        proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with dest, zi, 0
        Set zi to zi plus 1
    End While
    Let src_count be proc bigint_get_limb_count from BigInt with src
    If src_count is greater than dest_cap:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let ci be 0
    While ci is less than src_count:
        Let lv be proc bigint_get_limb from BigInt with src, ci
        proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with dest, ci, lv
        Set ci to ci plus 1
    End While
    proc bigint_set_limb_count from BigInt with dest, src_count
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Identity (point at infinity in Jacobian: Z = 0)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "curve_p256_point_set_infinity" takes pt as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Marks pt as the point at infinity. In Jacobian projective coordinates
    the infinity point is represented by Z = 0; X and Y are conventionally
    set to 1 to avoid divide-by-zero in any downstream conversions that
    fail to gate on the Z-check first.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Set X = 1, Y = 1, Z = 0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1) writes.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Public marker; no secret-dependent behaviour.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let x be proc curve_p256_point_x with pt
    Let y be proc curve_p256_point_y with pt
    Let z be proc curve_p256_point_z with pt
    Let x_cap be proc bigint_get_limb_capacity from BigInt with x
    Let xi be 0
    While xi is less than x_cap:
        proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with x, xi, 0
        Set xi to xi plus 1
    End While
    proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with x, 0, 1
    proc bigint_set_limb_count from BigInt with x, 1
    Let y_cap be proc bigint_get_limb_capacity from BigInt with y
    Let yi be 0
    While yi is less than y_cap:
        proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with y, yi, 0
        Set yi to yi plus 1
    End While
    proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with y, 0, 1
    proc bigint_set_limb_count from BigInt with y, 1
    Let z_cap be proc bigint_get_limb_capacity from BigInt with z
    Let zi be 0
    While zi is less than z_cap:
        proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with z, zi, 0
        Set zi to zi plus 1
    End While
    proc bigint_set_limb_count from BigInt with z, 0
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "curve_p256_point_is_infinity" takes pt as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns 1 if pt is the point at infinity (Z = 0), else 0.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Read Z component and test for zero via bigint_is_zero.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(limb_count) on Z.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Public predicate result.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let z be proc curve_p256_point_z with pt
    Return proc bigint_is_zero from BigInt with z
End Process

Process called "curve_p256_point_copy" takes arena as Integer, src as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns a fresh Jacobian point with the same X, Y, Z values as src.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Allocate a new point; copy each coordinate via curve_p256_field_copy_into.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Three field copies plus four allocations.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant time over field-element bit length.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let dst be proc curve_p256_point_alloc with arena
    If dst is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let sx be proc curve_p256_point_x with src
    Let sy be proc curve_p256_point_y with src
    Let sz be proc curve_p256_point_z with src
    Let dx be proc curve_p256_point_x with dst
    Let dy be proc curve_p256_point_y with dst
    Let dz be proc curve_p256_point_z with dst
    proc curve_p256_field_copy_into with dx, sx
    proc curve_p256_field_copy_into with dy, sy
    proc curve_p256_field_copy_into with dz, sz
    Return dst
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Generator point construction (affine -> Jacobian with Z=1)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "curve_p256_generator" takes arena as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the base point G in Jacobian coordinates (Gx, Gy, 1).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Allocate point; copy Gx into X, Gy into Y, set Z = 1.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Four arena allocations.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Public curve parameter.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let pt be proc curve_p256_point_alloc with arena
    If pt is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let gx be proc curve_p256_gx with arena
    Let gy be proc curve_p256_gy with arena
    If gx is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If gy is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let dx be proc curve_p256_point_x with pt
    Let dy be proc curve_p256_point_y with pt
    Let dz be proc curve_p256_point_z with pt
    proc curve_p256_field_copy_into with dx, gx
    proc curve_p256_field_copy_into with dy, gy
    proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with dz, 0, 1
    proc bigint_set_limb_count from BigInt with dz, 1
    Return pt
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Point negation (Jacobian: negate Y, X and Z unchanged)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "curve_p256_negate" takes arena as Integer, dest as Integer, pt as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Computes -P. For a Weierstrass curve, the inverse of (X, Y, Z) is
    (X, -Y mod p, Z).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Copy X and Z from pt to dest; compute dest.Y = (p - pt.Y) mod p via
    field_p256_neg.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One field negation plus two field copies.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Field negation is constant-time-bounded; the rest is pure copy.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let sx be proc curve_p256_point_x with pt
    Let sy be proc curve_p256_point_y with pt
    Let sz be proc curve_p256_point_z with pt
    Let dx be proc curve_p256_point_x with dest
    Let dy be proc curve_p256_point_y with dest
    Let dz be proc curve_p256_point_z with dest
    proc curve_p256_field_copy_into with dx, sx
    proc curve_p256_field_copy_into with dz, sz
    Return proc field_p256_neg from Field with arena, dy, sy
End Process

Note:
================================================================================
Point doubling (Jacobian for a = -3 curves)
Formulas from Bernstein-Lange and Hankerson-Menezes-Vanstone alg 3.21:
   if Y1 = 0 -> infinity
   delta = Z1^2
   gamma = Y1^2
   beta  = X1 * gamma
   alpha = 3 * (X1 - delta) * (X1 + delta)
   X3 = alpha^2 - 8*beta
   Z3 = (Y1 + Z1)^2 - gamma - delta
   Y3 = alpha * (4*beta - X3) - 8 * gamma^2
================================================================================
:End Note

Process called "curve_p256_double" takes arena as Integer, dest as Integer, pt as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Doubles a point on the curve using a = -3 optimized Jacobian formulas.
    Doubling is required for every bit of the scalar in a binary ladder and
    is therefore the inner-loop bottleneck of scalar multiplication.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. If pt is infinity, dest = infinity, return.
    2. Compute the intermediate field elements delta, gamma, beta, alpha
       as defined by the Bernstein-Lange formula for a = -3 curves.
    3. Compose dest.X, dest.Y, dest.Z from these intermediates.
    All operations use field_p256_* primitives so reductions mod p are
    handled automatically.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    4 field squarings + 4 field multiplications + 9 field additions/
    subtractions. ~30 us at P-256 size.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The branch on infinity is on a public-derived flag (the accumulator
    is only at infinity on the very first bit; for the variable-base
    case the input point is public to the protocol). The body has no
    secret-dependent branching.
    @End Security_Scope

    If proc curve_p256_point_is_infinity with pt is equal to 1:
        Return proc curve_p256_point_set_infinity with dest
    End If

    Let x1 be proc curve_p256_point_x with pt
    Let y1 be proc curve_p256_point_y with pt
    Let z1 be proc curve_p256_point_z with pt

    Note: Detect 2-torsion: if Y1 == 0 the doubled point is infinity.
    If proc bigint_is_zero from BigInt with y1 is equal to 1:
        Return proc curve_p256_point_set_infinity with dest
    End If

    Let delta be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    Let gamma be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    Let beta be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    Let alpha be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    Let t1 be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    Let t2 be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    Let t3 be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    Let t4 be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    Let t5 be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena

    Note: delta = Z1^2
    proc field_p256_sqr from Field with arena, delta, z1
    Note: gamma = Y1^2
    proc field_p256_sqr from Field with arena, gamma, y1
    Note: beta = X1 * gamma
    proc field_p256_mul from Field with arena, beta, x1, gamma

    Note: alpha = 3 * (X1 - delta) * (X1 + delta)
    proc field_p256_sub from Field with arena, t1, x1, delta
    proc field_p256_add from Field with arena, t2, x1, delta
    proc field_p256_mul from Field with arena, t3, t1, t2
    Note: t3 contains (X1-delta)(X1+delta); multiply by 3 via two adds.
    proc field_p256_add from Field with arena, t4, t3, t3
    proc field_p256_add from Field with arena, alpha, t4, t3

    Note: X3 = alpha^2 - 8*beta
    Let alpha_sq be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    proc field_p256_sqr from Field with arena, alpha_sq, alpha
    Note: eight_beta = 8 * beta
    Let two_beta be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    proc field_p256_add from Field with arena, two_beta, beta, beta
    Let four_beta be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    proc field_p256_add from Field with arena, four_beta, two_beta, two_beta
    Let eight_beta be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    proc field_p256_add from Field with arena, eight_beta, four_beta, four_beta

    Let dx be proc curve_p256_point_x with dest
    proc field_p256_sub from Field with arena, dx, alpha_sq, eight_beta

    Note: Z3 = (Y1 + Z1)^2 - gamma - delta
    proc field_p256_add from Field with arena, t5, y1, z1
    Let y1z1_sq be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    proc field_p256_sqr from Field with arena, y1z1_sq, t5
    Let z3_tmp be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    proc field_p256_sub from Field with arena, z3_tmp, y1z1_sq, gamma
    Let dz be proc curve_p256_point_z with dest
    proc field_p256_sub from Field with arena, dz, z3_tmp, delta

    Note: Y3 = alpha * (4*beta - X3) - 8 * gamma^2
    Let dx_copy be proc field_p256_copy from Field with arena, dx
    Let diff4b_x3 be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    proc field_p256_sub from Field with arena, diff4b_x3, four_beta, dx_copy
    Let alpha_term be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    proc field_p256_mul from Field with arena, alpha_term, alpha, diff4b_x3
    Let gamma_sq be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    proc field_p256_sqr from Field with arena, gamma_sq, gamma
    Let two_g2 be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    proc field_p256_add from Field with arena, two_g2, gamma_sq, gamma_sq
    Let four_g2 be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    proc field_p256_add from Field with arena, four_g2, two_g2, two_g2
    Let eight_g2 be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    proc field_p256_add from Field with arena, eight_g2, four_g2, four_g2

    Let dy be proc curve_p256_point_y with dest
    proc field_p256_sub from Field with arena, dy, alpha_term, eight_g2

    Return 1
End Process

Note:
================================================================================
Point addition (Jacobian + Jacobian = Jacobian)
Bernstein-Lange complete formulas for distinct, non-symmetric inputs.
   U1 = X1 * Z2^2
   U2 = X2 * Z1^2
   S1 = Y1 * Z2^3
   S2 = Y2 * Z1^3
   if U1 == U2:
       if S1 != S2: return infinity (P + (-P))
       else        : return double(P)
   H = U2 - U1
   R = S2 - S1
   X3 = R^2 - H^3 - 2*U1*H^2
   Y3 = R*(U1*H^2 - X3) - S1*H^3
   Z3 = Z1 * Z2 * H
================================================================================
:End Note

Process called "curve_p256_add" takes arena as Integer, dest as Integer, p1 as Integer, p2 as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Adds two Jacobian points using the standard add formulas. Handles
    the exceptional cases by explicit comparison: identity element,
    symmetric point (P + (-P) = infinity), and equal-point case
    (P + P = double(P)).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Identity short-circuits: P1=inf -> dest = P2 (copy); P2=inf -> dest = P1.
    2. Compute U1, U2, S1, S2.
    3. If U1 == U2: dispatch to double or infinity based on S1 vs S2.
    4. Otherwise apply the canonical formulas above.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Approx 11 field multiplications + 5 squarings + several additions.
    ~80 us at P-256 size.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Branches on identity and equal-point cases. For the ECDSA verify
    path the inputs are public so this is acceptable. The
    curve_p256_scalar_mul ladder used in signing uses a different
    constant-time conditional select to avoid leaking through these
    branches.
    @End Security_Scope

    If proc curve_p256_point_is_infinity with p1 is equal to 1:
        Let dx_i be proc curve_p256_point_x with dest
        Let dy_i be proc curve_p256_point_y with dest
        Let dz_i be proc curve_p256_point_z with dest
        Let sx_i be proc curve_p256_point_x with p2
        Let sy_i be proc curve_p256_point_y with p2
        Let sz_i be proc curve_p256_point_z with p2
        proc curve_p256_field_copy_into with dx_i, sx_i
        proc curve_p256_field_copy_into with dy_i, sy_i
        proc curve_p256_field_copy_into with dz_i, sz_i
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc curve_p256_point_is_infinity with p2 is equal to 1:
        Let dx_j be proc curve_p256_point_x with dest
        Let dy_j be proc curve_p256_point_y with dest
        Let dz_j be proc curve_p256_point_z with dest
        Let sx_j be proc curve_p256_point_x with p1
        Let sy_j be proc curve_p256_point_y with p1
        Let sz_j be proc curve_p256_point_z with p1
        proc curve_p256_field_copy_into with dx_j, sx_j
        proc curve_p256_field_copy_into with dy_j, sy_j
        proc curve_p256_field_copy_into with dz_j, sz_j
        Return 1
    End If

    Let x1 be proc curve_p256_point_x with p1
    Let y1 be proc curve_p256_point_y with p1
    Let z1 be proc curve_p256_point_z with p1
    Let x2 be proc curve_p256_point_x with p2
    Let y2 be proc curve_p256_point_y with p2
    Let z2 be proc curve_p256_point_z with p2

    Let z1_sq be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    Let z2_sq be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    Let z1_cu be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    Let z2_cu be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    Let u1 be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    Let u2 be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    Let s1 be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    Let s2 be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena

    proc field_p256_sqr from Field with arena, z1_sq, z1
    proc field_p256_sqr from Field with arena, z2_sq, z2
    proc field_p256_mul from Field with arena, z1_cu, z1_sq, z1
    proc field_p256_mul from Field with arena, z2_cu, z2_sq, z2
    proc field_p256_mul from Field with arena, u1, x1, z2_sq
    proc field_p256_mul from Field with arena, u2, x2, z1_sq
    proc field_p256_mul from Field with arena, s1, y1, z2_cu
    proc field_p256_mul from Field with arena, s2, y2, z1_cu

    Let u_eq be proc field_p256_equal from Field with u1, u2
    If u_eq is equal to 1:
        Let s_eq be proc field_p256_equal from Field with s1, s2
        If s_eq is equal to 1:
            Return proc curve_p256_double with arena, dest, p1
        End If
        Return proc curve_p256_point_set_infinity with dest
    End If

    Let h be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    Let r be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    proc field_p256_sub from Field with arena, h, u2, u1
    proc field_p256_sub from Field with arena, r, s2, s1

    Let h_sq be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    Let h_cu be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    proc field_p256_sqr from Field with arena, h_sq, h
    proc field_p256_mul from Field with arena, h_cu, h_sq, h

    Let u1_h_sq be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    proc field_p256_mul from Field with arena, u1_h_sq, u1, h_sq

    Note: X3 = R^2 - H^3 - 2*U1*H^2
    Let r_sq be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    proc field_p256_sqr from Field with arena, r_sq, r
    Let two_u1_h_sq be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    proc field_p256_add from Field with arena, two_u1_h_sq, u1_h_sq, u1_h_sq
    Let x3_term1 be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    proc field_p256_sub from Field with arena, x3_term1, r_sq, h_cu

    Let dx be proc curve_p256_point_x with dest
    proc field_p256_sub from Field with arena, dx, x3_term1, two_u1_h_sq

    Note: Y3 = R*(U1*H^2 - X3) - S1*H^3
    Let dx_now be proc field_p256_copy from Field with arena, dx
    Let inner be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    proc field_p256_sub from Field with arena, inner, u1_h_sq, dx_now
    Let r_inner be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    proc field_p256_mul from Field with arena, r_inner, r, inner
    Let s1_h_cu be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    proc field_p256_mul from Field with arena, s1_h_cu, s1, h_cu

    Let dy be proc curve_p256_point_y with dest
    proc field_p256_sub from Field with arena, dy, r_inner, s1_h_cu

    Note: Z3 = Z1 * Z2 * H
    Let z1z2 be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    proc field_p256_mul from Field with arena, z1z2, z1, z2
    Let dz be proc curve_p256_point_z with dest
    proc field_p256_mul from Field with arena, dz, z1z2, h

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Constant-time conditional point copy
Note: Used by the constant-time scalar multiplication ladder. When cond == 1,
Note: dest <- src. When cond == 0, dest is left unchanged. Both branches walk
Note: the same memory so timing is independent of cond.
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "curve_p256_cmov" takes dest as Integer, src as Integer, cond as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Branchless conditional copy of one Jacobian point's three BigInt
    component values from src into dest. Required for constant-time
    scalar multiplication: the per-bit ladder must always touch both
    candidate accumulators regardless of the scalar bit.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Build a 64-bit mask m = -cond (all 1s when cond = 1, all 0s when
    cond = 0). For each limb i of each coordinate compute
       dest_limb[i] = (dest_limb[i] AND NOT m) OR (src_limb[i] AND m).
    This walks the full 4-limb (256-bit) capacity of each coordinate
    regardless of the actual numerical limb count.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    12 limb writes per call (3 coords * 4 limbs).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Hardened against timing-based scalar leakage. No data-dependent
    branch within the limb loop.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let mask be 0 minus cond
    Let inv_mask be mask bitwise_xor 18446744073709551615

    Let dx be proc curve_p256_point_x with dest
    Let dy be proc curve_p256_point_y with dest
    Let dz be proc curve_p256_point_z with dest
    Let sx be proc curve_p256_point_x with src
    Let sy be proc curve_p256_point_y with src
    Let sz be proc curve_p256_point_z with src

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than CURVE_P256_LIMBS:
        Let d_lx be proc bigint_get_limb from BigInt with dx, i
        Let s_lx be proc bigint_get_limb from BigInt with sx, i
        Let new_x be d_lx bitwise_and inv_mask
        Let s_x_masked be s_lx bitwise_and mask
        Set new_x to new_x bitwise_or s_x_masked
        proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with dx, i, new_x

        Let d_ly be proc bigint_get_limb from BigInt with dy, i
        Let s_ly be proc bigint_get_limb from BigInt with sy, i
        Let new_y be d_ly bitwise_and inv_mask
        Let s_y_masked be s_ly bitwise_and mask
        Set new_y to new_y bitwise_or s_y_masked
        proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with dy, i, new_y

        Let d_lz be proc bigint_get_limb from BigInt with dz, i
        Let s_lz be proc bigint_get_limb from BigInt with sz, i
        Let new_z be d_lz bitwise_and inv_mask
        Let s_z_masked be s_lz bitwise_and mask
        Set new_z to new_z bitwise_or s_z_masked
        proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with dz, i, new_z

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Let scount be proc bigint_get_limb_count from BigInt with sx
    Let dcount_x be proc bigint_get_limb_count from BigInt with dx
    Let new_count_x be dcount_x bitwise_and inv_mask
    Set new_count_x to new_count_x bitwise_or scount bitwise_and mask
    proc bigint_set_limb_count from BigInt with dx, new_count_x

    Let scount_y be proc bigint_get_limb_count from BigInt with sy
    Let dcount_y be proc bigint_get_limb_count from BigInt with dy
    Let new_count_y be dcount_y bitwise_and inv_mask
    Set new_count_y to new_count_y bitwise_or scount_y bitwise_and mask
    proc bigint_set_limb_count from BigInt with dy, new_count_y

    Let scount_z be proc bigint_get_limb_count from BigInt with sz
    Let dcount_z be proc bigint_get_limb_count from BigInt with dz
    Let new_count_z be dcount_z bitwise_and inv_mask
    Set new_count_z to new_count_z bitwise_or scount_z bitwise_and mask
    proc bigint_set_limb_count from BigInt with dz, new_count_z

    Return 1
End Process

Note:
================================================================================
Constant-time scalar multiplication: dest = k * P

Algorithm: Montgomery ladder over the curve. Maintains two accumulators
R0 and R1 with the invariant R1 - R0 = P after every iteration. For each
scalar bit b from MSB to LSB:
   if b == 0:  R1 = R0 + R1, R0 = 2*R0
   if b == 1:  R0 = R0 + R1, R1 = 2*R1
At the end R0 = k*P.

The branch on b is realized via constant-time point swaps before and
after the (add, double) pair so each iteration performs the same
sequence of operations regardless of b.
================================================================================
:End Note

Process called "curve_p256_scalar_mul" takes arena as Integer, dest as Integer, scalar as Integer, base as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Computes dest = scalar * base on the curve. Constant-time over the
    256-bit width of the scalar via a Montgomery ladder with conditional
    swaps. This is the secret-key-safe variant used by ECDSA signing.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Initialize R0 = infinity, R1 = base.
    2. For each bit b of scalar from bit 255 to bit 0:
       a. Use a constant-time conditional swap to bring the
          "active" accumulator into R0.
       b. Compute (R0 + R1) into a fresh temporary, double R1 into
          another fresh temporary, then write back.
       c. After the inner step, swap back so R0 holds the bit-zero
          accumulator and R1 holds the bit-one accumulator for the
          next iteration.
    3. Copy R0 into dest.

    Each scalar bit costs exactly: 4 cmov + 1 point add + 1 point double.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    256 iterations. At ~110 us per iteration (point add + point double)
    this is roughly 30 ms total per scalar multiplication. Acceptable
    for ECDSA sign/verify at typical message rates; future optimizations
    (Montgomery field arithmetic, wNAF tables for fixed-base) can drop
    this by an order of magnitude.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Hardened against:
    - Simple Power Analysis (SPA): the ladder issues a fixed instruction
      sequence per bit regardless of bit value.
    - Branch-prediction leakage of the scalar: no scalar bit is used in
      a conditional branch; only XOR'd into the cmov masks.
    - Cache-side timing on table accesses: this implementation uses no
      precomputed lookup tables.

    Out of scope:
    - Fault injection (the caller must validate the result is on-curve
      after returning to detect tampering).
    - Memory zeroization of arena scratch (the caller's arena reset is
      responsible).

    References:
    - Montgomery, "Speeding the Pollard and elliptic curve methods of
      factorization", Math. Comp. 1987.
    - Joye, Yen "The Montgomery powering ladder" CHES 2002.
    @End Security_Scope

    If dest is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If scalar is equal to 0:
        Return proc curve_p256_point_set_infinity with dest
    End If
    If base is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let r0 be proc curve_p256_point_alloc with arena
    If r0 is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let r1 be proc curve_p256_point_alloc with arena
    If r1 is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc curve_p256_point_set_infinity with r0
    Let base_x_ptr be proc curve_p256_point_x with base
    Let base_y_ptr be proc curve_p256_point_y with base
    Let base_z_ptr be proc curve_p256_point_z with base
    Let r1x be proc curve_p256_point_x with r1
    Let r1y be proc curve_p256_point_y with r1
    Let r1z be proc curve_p256_point_z with r1
    proc curve_p256_field_copy_into with r1x, base_x_ptr
    proc curve_p256_field_copy_into with r1y, base_y_ptr
    proc curve_p256_field_copy_into with r1z, base_z_ptr

    Note: Walk scalar bits from MSB to LSB. The scalar has at most 4 limbs.
    Let limb_idx_plus_one be CURVE_P256_LIMBS
    While limb_idx_plus_one is greater than 0:
        Let limb_idx be limb_idx_plus_one minus 1
        Let limb_value be proc bigint_get_limb from BigInt with scalar, limb_idx
        Let bit_idx_plus_one be 64
        While bit_idx_plus_one is greater than 0:
            Let bit_idx be bit_idx_plus_one minus 1
            Note: Extract this bit of the scalar.
            Let mask_val be 1
            Let shift_iter be 0
            While shift_iter is less than bit_idx:
                Set mask_val to mask_val multiplied by 2
                Set shift_iter to shift_iter plus 1
            End While
            Let masked be limb_value bitwise_and mask_val
            Let bit be 0
            If masked is not equal to 0:
                Set bit to 1
            End If

            Note: Allocate fresh accumulators each round so arithmetic
            Note: writes do not stomp on the operands of subsequent
            Note: operations within the same iteration.
            Let new_r0 be proc curve_p256_point_alloc with arena
            Let new_r1 be proc curve_p256_point_alloc with arena
            If new_r0 is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If
            If new_r1 is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If

            Note: Compute add = R0 + R1 and dbl0 = 2*R0 unconditionally.
            Note: We also compute dbl1 = 2*R1.
            Let added be proc curve_p256_point_alloc with arena
            Let dbl0 be proc curve_p256_point_alloc with arena
            Let dbl1 be proc curve_p256_point_alloc with arena
            If added is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If
            If dbl0 is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If
            If dbl1 is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If
            proc curve_p256_add with arena, added, r0, r1
            proc curve_p256_double with arena, dbl0, r0
            proc curve_p256_double with arena, dbl1, r1

            Note: For bit==0: R1' = added, R0' = dbl0.
            Note: For bit==1: R0' = added, R1' = dbl1.
            Note: Implement via constant-time cmov.
            Note: First set new_r0 = dbl0 unconditionally, then overwrite with
            Note: added when bit == 1.
            Let bit_inv be 1 minus bit
            proc curve_p256_cmov with new_r0, dbl0, bit_inv
            proc curve_p256_cmov with new_r0, added, bit
            proc curve_p256_cmov with new_r1, added, bit_inv
            proc curve_p256_cmov with new_r1, dbl1, bit

            Note: Copy back from new_r0/new_r1 into r0/r1 buffers.
            Let nr0x be proc curve_p256_point_x with new_r0
            Let nr0y be proc curve_p256_point_y with new_r0
            Let nr0z be proc curve_p256_point_z with new_r0
            Let r0x be proc curve_p256_point_x with r0
            Let r0y be proc curve_p256_point_y with r0
            Let r0z be proc curve_p256_point_z with r0
            proc curve_p256_field_copy_into with r0x, nr0x
            proc curve_p256_field_copy_into with r0y, nr0y
            proc curve_p256_field_copy_into with r0z, nr0z

            Let nr1x be proc curve_p256_point_x with new_r1
            Let nr1y be proc curve_p256_point_y with new_r1
            Let nr1z be proc curve_p256_point_z with new_r1
            Let r1x_now be proc curve_p256_point_x with r1
            Let r1y_now be proc curve_p256_point_y with r1
            Let r1z_now be proc curve_p256_point_z with r1
            proc curve_p256_field_copy_into with r1x_now, nr1x
            proc curve_p256_field_copy_into with r1y_now, nr1y
            proc curve_p256_field_copy_into with r1z_now, nr1z

            Set bit_idx_plus_one to bit_idx_plus_one minus 1
        End While
        Set limb_idx_plus_one to limb_idx_plus_one minus 1
    End While

    Note: Copy R0 into dest.
    Let r0x_out be proc curve_p256_point_x with r0
    Let r0y_out be proc curve_p256_point_y with r0
    Let r0z_out be proc curve_p256_point_z with r0
    Let dx_out be proc curve_p256_point_x with dest
    Let dy_out be proc curve_p256_point_y with dest
    Let dz_out be proc curve_p256_point_z with dest
    proc curve_p256_field_copy_into with dx_out, r0x_out
    proc curve_p256_field_copy_into with dy_out, r0y_out
    proc curve_p256_field_copy_into with dz_out, r0z_out
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Affine conversion: (X, Y, Z) Jacobian -> (x, y) affine where
Note:   x = X / Z^2  and  y = Y / Z^3
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "curve_p256_to_affine" takes arena as Integer, pt as Integer, out_x as Integer, out_y as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Converts a Jacobian point to affine coordinates. Returns 0 if the
    point is at infinity (cannot be represented in affine form).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. If Z == 0, return 0.
    2. Compute z_inv = Z^-1 mod p via field_p256_inv.
    3. z_inv_sq = z_inv^2, z_inv_cu = z_inv^3.
    4. out_x = X * z_inv_sq, out_y = Y * z_inv_cu.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One field inversion (dominant, ~1 ms) plus four multiplications.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Field inversion uses Fermat's-method modular exponentiation which
    is constant-time over the exponent (fixed: p-2). Multiplications
    are constant-time over loop bounds.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let z be proc curve_p256_point_z with pt
    If proc bigint_is_zero from BigInt with z is equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let z_inv be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    Let inv_rc be proc field_p256_inv from Field with arena, z_inv, z
    If inv_rc is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let z_inv_sq be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    proc field_p256_sqr from Field with arena, z_inv_sq, z_inv
    Let z_inv_cu be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    proc field_p256_mul from Field with arena, z_inv_cu, z_inv_sq, z_inv
    Let x be proc curve_p256_point_x with pt
    Let y be proc curve_p256_point_y with pt
    proc field_p256_mul from Field with arena, out_x, x, z_inv_sq
    proc field_p256_mul from Field with arena, out_y, y, z_inv_cu
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Point validation: confirms y^2 == x^3 - 3x + b (mod p) in affine form
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "curve_p256_is_on_curve_affine" takes arena as Integer, x as Integer, y as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns 1 if (x, y) satisfies the P-256 curve equation. Used to
    validate decoded peer public keys before they are admitted into a
    protocol (ECDH, ECDSA verify).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. lhs = y^2 mod p.
    2. rhs = x^3 - 3*x + b mod p.
    3. Compare equality.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Five field multiplications plus a few additions. ~150 us.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Inputs are public peer points; the comparison itself is constant-
    time via field_p256_equal.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let lhs be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    proc field_p256_sqr from Field with arena, lhs, y

    Let x_sq be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    proc field_p256_sqr from Field with arena, x_sq, x
    Let x_cu be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    proc field_p256_mul from Field with arena, x_cu, x_sq, x

    Note: 3*x via two additions.
    Let two_x be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    proc field_p256_add from Field with arena, two_x, x, x
    Let three_x be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    proc field_p256_add from Field with arena, three_x, two_x, x

    Let rhs_tmp be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    proc field_p256_sub from Field with arena, rhs_tmp, x_cu, three_x

    Let b be proc curve_p256_b with arena
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let rhs be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    proc field_p256_add from Field with arena, rhs, rhs_tmp, b

    Return proc field_p256_equal from Field with lhs, rhs
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Point encoding (SEC 1 v2.0 section 2.3.3)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "curve_p256_encode_uncompressed" takes arena as Integer, pt as Integer, out_bytes as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Writes the 65-byte uncompressed encoding 0x04 || X || Y of the
    affine form of pt into out_bytes.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Convert to affine. If infinity, write a single 0x00 byte and
       return 1.
    2. Write 0x04 followed by X big-endian (32 bytes) and Y big-endian
       (32 bytes).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Dominated by the affine conversion (~1 ms) plus 65 byte writes.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Output is public. Constant time on the byte loop.
    @End Security_Scope

    If proc curve_p256_point_is_infinity with pt is equal to 1:
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with out_bytes, 0, 0
        Return 1
    End If
    Let ax be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    Let ay be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    Let aff_rc be proc curve_p256_to_affine with arena, pt, ax, ay
    If aff_rc is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with out_bytes, 0, 4
    proc field_p256_pack from Field with ax, out_bytes plus 1
    proc field_p256_pack from Field with ay, out_bytes plus 33
    Return CURVE_P256_POINT_BYTES
End Process

Process called "curve_p256_encode_compressed" takes arena as Integer, pt as Integer, out_bytes as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Writes the 33-byte compressed encoding (0x02 or 0x03) || X of pt
    into out_bytes. Tag byte is 0x02 when y is even, 0x03 when odd.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Convert to affine. Infinity short-circuits to a single 0x00.
    2. Inspect y's low limb's least-significant bit; tag = 0x02 + (y_bit).
    3. Pack X big-endian.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Affine conversion plus 33 byte writes.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Output is public.
    @End Security_Scope

    If proc curve_p256_point_is_infinity with pt is equal to 1:
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with out_bytes, 0, 0
        Return 1
    End If
    Let ax be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    Let ay be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    Let aff_rc be proc curve_p256_to_affine with arena, pt, ax, ay
    If aff_rc is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let y_low be proc bigint_get_limb from BigInt with ay, 0
    Let y_parity be y_low bitwise_and 1
    Let tag be 2 plus y_parity
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with out_bytes, 0, tag
    proc field_p256_pack from Field with ax, out_bytes plus 1
    Return CURVE_P256_COMPRESSED_BYTES
End Process

Process called "curve_p256_encode_hybrid" takes arena as Integer, pt as Integer, out_bytes as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Writes the 65-byte hybrid encoding (0x06 or 0x07) || X || Y where
    the low bit of the tag carries the y-parity. See SEC 1 v2.0 2.3.5.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Convert to affine.
    2. Inspect y parity; tag = 0x06 + parity.
    3. Pack X and Y.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Same cost as uncompressed encoding.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Output is public.
    @End Security_Scope

    If proc curve_p256_point_is_infinity with pt is equal to 1:
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with out_bytes, 0, 0
        Return 1
    End If
    Let ax be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    Let ay be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    Let aff_rc be proc curve_p256_to_affine with arena, pt, ax, ay
    If aff_rc is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let y_low be proc bigint_get_limb from BigInt with ay, 0
    Let y_parity be y_low bitwise_and 1
    Let tag be 6 plus y_parity
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with out_bytes, 0, tag
    proc field_p256_pack from Field with ax, out_bytes plus 1
    proc field_p256_pack from Field with ay, out_bytes plus 33
    Return CURVE_P256_POINT_BYTES
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Point decoding (decompression support deferred to compressed-only path
Note: via Tonelli-Shanks, which uses field_p256_inv-style modular exponentiation
Note: with the special exponent (p+1)/4 since p === 3 (mod 4) for P-256.
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "curve_p256_decode_uncompressed" takes arena as Integer, in_bytes as Integer, in_len as Integer, out_pt as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Parses a 65-byte 0x04 || X || Y uncompressed encoding into Jacobian
    coordinates (Z = 1) and validates the resulting (X, Y) lies on the
    curve. Returns 0 on length mismatch, tag mismatch, or off-curve.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Check length == 65 and tag == 0x04.
    2. Unpack X, Y as field elements (reducing modulo p).
    3. Validate via curve_p256_is_on_curve_affine.
    4. Copy X, Y into out_pt; set Z = 1.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Two unpacks (~200 ns each) plus one on-curve check (~150 us).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Required for ECDH/ECDSA where peer keys must be validated to avoid
    invalid-curve attacks (Antipa et al. 2003).
    @End Security_Scope

    If in_len is not equal to CURVE_P256_POINT_BYTES:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let tag be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with in_bytes, 0
    If tag is not equal to 4:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let x_in be proc field_p256_unpack from Field with arena, in_bytes plus 1
    Let y_in be proc field_p256_unpack from Field with arena, in_bytes plus 33
    If x_in is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If y_in is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let on_curve be proc curve_p256_is_on_curve_affine with arena, x_in, y_in
    If on_curve is not equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let dx be proc curve_p256_point_x with out_pt
    Let dy be proc curve_p256_point_y with out_pt
    Let dz be proc curve_p256_point_z with out_pt
    proc curve_p256_field_copy_into with dx, x_in
    proc curve_p256_field_copy_into with dy, y_in
    Let dz_cap be proc bigint_get_limb_capacity from BigInt with dz
    Let zi be 0
    While zi is less than dz_cap:
        proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with dz, zi, 0
        Set zi to zi plus 1
    End While
    proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with dz, 0, 1
    proc bigint_set_limb_count from BigInt with dz, 1
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "curve_p256_decode_compressed" takes arena as Integer, in_bytes as Integer, in_len as Integer, out_pt as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Parses a 33-byte (0x02|0x03) || X compressed encoding. Recovers
    y by computing y^2 = x^3 - 3x + b mod p, then taking a square root.
    Because P-256's prime p satisfies p === 3 (mod 4), the square root
    is y = (y^2)^((p+1)/4) mod p; if y has the wrong parity we negate it.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Check length == 33 and tag in {0x02, 0x03}.
    2. Unpack X.
    3. Compute u = x^3 - 3x + b.
    4. Build exponent e = (p+1)/4 as a BigInt: this is the bit-shift of
       (p+1) by 2 right.
    5. y = u^e mod p via bigint_mod_exp.
    6. Verify y^2 == u (rejects non-residues).
    7. If parity of y mismatches tag, y = p - y.
    8. Copy X, Y into out_pt; set Z = 1.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One modular exponentiation (~1.5 ms) dominates.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Input is public.
    @End Security_Scope

    If in_len is not equal to CURVE_P256_COMPRESSED_BYTES:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let tag be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with in_bytes, 0
    Let want_parity be 0
    If tag is equal to 2:
        Set want_parity to 0
    Otherwise:
        If tag is equal to 3:
            Set want_parity to 1
        Otherwise:
            Return 0
        End If
    End If
    Let x_in be proc field_p256_unpack from Field with arena, in_bytes plus 1
    If x_in is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: u = x^3 - 3x + b
    Let x_sq be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    proc field_p256_sqr from Field with arena, x_sq, x_in
    Let x_cu be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    proc field_p256_mul from Field with arena, x_cu, x_sq, x_in
    Let two_x be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    proc field_p256_add from Field with arena, two_x, x_in, x_in
    Let three_x be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    proc field_p256_add from Field with arena, three_x, two_x, x_in
    Let u_tmp be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    proc field_p256_sub from Field with arena, u_tmp, x_cu, three_x
    Let b be proc curve_p256_b with arena
    Let u be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    proc field_p256_add from Field with arena, u, u_tmp, b

    Note: exponent e = (p+1)/4. Build p, increment, then right-shift by 2.
    Let p be proc field_p256_prime from Field with arena
    Let one be proc bigint_from_u64 from BigInt with arena, 1
    Let p_plus_one be proc bigint_alloc from BigInt with arena, 10
    proc bigint_add from BigInt with p_plus_one, p, one
    proc bigint_shift_right_one from BigIntX with p_plus_one
    proc bigint_shift_right_one from BigIntX with p_plus_one

    Let y_cand be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    proc bigint_mod_exp from BigInt with arena, y_cand, u, p_plus_one, p

    Note: Verify y_cand^2 == u (i.e. u was a quadratic residue).
    Let y_sq_check be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    proc field_p256_sqr from Field with arena, y_sq_check, y_cand
    If proc field_p256_equal from Field with y_sq_check, u is not equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let y_low be proc bigint_get_limb from BigInt with y_cand, 0
    Let y_parity be y_low bitwise_and 1
    If y_parity is not equal to want_parity:
        Let neg_y be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
        proc field_p256_neg from Field with arena, neg_y, y_cand
        Let dx be proc curve_p256_point_x with out_pt
        Let dy be proc curve_p256_point_y with out_pt
        Let dz be proc curve_p256_point_z with out_pt
        proc curve_p256_field_copy_into with dx, x_in
        proc curve_p256_field_copy_into with dy, neg_y
        Let dz_cap be proc bigint_get_limb_capacity from BigInt with dz
        Let zi be 0
        While zi is less than dz_cap:
            proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with dz, zi, 0
            Set zi to zi plus 1
        End While
        proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with dz, 0, 1
        proc bigint_set_limb_count from BigInt with dz, 1
        Return 1
    End If

    Let dx2 be proc curve_p256_point_x with out_pt
    Let dy2 be proc curve_p256_point_y with out_pt
    Let dz2 be proc curve_p256_point_z with out_pt
    proc curve_p256_field_copy_into with dx2, x_in
    proc curve_p256_field_copy_into with dy2, y_cand
    Let dz2_cap be proc bigint_get_limb_capacity from BigInt with dz2
    Let zi2 be 0
    While zi2 is less than dz2_cap:
        proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with dz2, zi2, 0
        Set zi2 to zi2 plus 1
    End While
    proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with dz2, 0, 1
    proc bigint_set_limb_count from BigInt with dz2, 1
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "curve_p256_decode" takes arena as Integer, in_bytes as Integer, in_len as Integer, out_pt as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Dispatching decoder: routes to uncompressed, compressed, or hybrid
    based on the first byte. Returns 0 for unknown encodings.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Switch on the leading tag byte. For 0x06/0x07 hybrid form we drop
    the parity bit and parse as uncompressed (ignoring the redundant
    parity since X || Y is already complete).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Lookup table plus one nested decode.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Input is public.
    @End Security_Scope

    If in_len is less than 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let tag be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with in_bytes, 0
    If tag is equal to 4:
        Return proc curve_p256_decode_uncompressed with arena, in_bytes, in_len, out_pt
    End If
    If tag is equal to 6:
        Return proc curve_p256_decode_uncompressed_hybrid with arena, in_bytes, in_len, out_pt, 0
    End If
    If tag is equal to 7:
        Return proc curve_p256_decode_uncompressed_hybrid with arena, in_bytes, in_len, out_pt, 1
    End If
    If tag is equal to 2:
        Return proc curve_p256_decode_compressed with arena, in_bytes, in_len, out_pt
    End If
    If tag is equal to 3:
        Return proc curve_p256_decode_compressed with arena, in_bytes, in_len, out_pt
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "curve_p256_decode_uncompressed_hybrid" takes arena as Integer, in_bytes as Integer, in_len as Integer, out_pt as Integer, want_parity as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Parses a hybrid 0x06/0x07 || X || Y encoding. Both X and Y are
    present so the parity bit in the tag is redundant; we still verify
    it matches the actual Y parity for strict-DER conformance.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Check length == 65.
    2. Unpack X and Y.
    3. Verify Y parity matches want_parity.
    4. Verify on-curve and store in Jacobian form (Z = 1).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Two unpacks plus on-curve check.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Input is public.
    @End Security_Scope

    If in_len is not equal to CURVE_P256_POINT_BYTES:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let x_in be proc field_p256_unpack from Field with arena, in_bytes plus 1
    Let y_in be proc field_p256_unpack from Field with arena, in_bytes plus 33
    If x_in is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If y_in is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let y_low be proc bigint_get_limb from BigInt with y_in, 0
    Let y_parity be y_low bitwise_and 1
    If y_parity is not equal to want_parity:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let on_curve be proc curve_p256_is_on_curve_affine with arena, x_in, y_in
    If on_curve is not equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let dx be proc curve_p256_point_x with out_pt
    Let dy be proc curve_p256_point_y with out_pt
    Let dz be proc curve_p256_point_z with out_pt
    proc curve_p256_field_copy_into with dx, x_in
    proc curve_p256_field_copy_into with dy, y_in
    Let dz_cap be proc bigint_get_limb_capacity from BigInt with dz
    Let zi be 0
    While zi is less than dz_cap:
        proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with dz, zi, 0
        Set zi to zi plus 1
    End While
    proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with dz, 0, 1
    proc bigint_set_limb_count from BigInt with dz, 1
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Subgroup check. For P-256 the cofactor is 1, so any point on the curve
Note: is already in the prime-order subgroup; the on-curve check suffices.
Note: This entry point is provided for API symmetry with curves where cofactor
Note: > 1 (Curve25519, Ed25519) and for callers that want explicit confirmation.
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "curve_p256_validate_public_key" takes arena as Integer, pt as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Validates a peer's public key per SEC 1 v2.0 section 3.2.2. For
    P-256 specifically:
    - reject point-at-infinity,
    - check coordinates are < p (handled by field_p256_unpack's mod-p
      reduction at decode time),
    - check the point lies on the curve,
    - confirm prime-order subgroup membership (trivial for cofactor-1
      curves but check explicitly).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Reject infinity.
    2. Compute (x_aff, y_aff) and run is_on_curve_affine.
    3. Since cofactor = 1, subgroup membership coincides with on-curve.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Affine conversion plus on-curve check.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Mandatory for preventing invalid-curve attacks (Antipa, Brown,
    Menezes, Struik, Vanstone CRYPTO 2003).
    @End Security_Scope

    If proc curve_p256_point_is_infinity with pt is equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let ax be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    Let ay be proc field_p256_zero from Field with arena
    Let aff_rc be proc curve_p256_to_affine with arena, pt, ax, ay
    If aff_rc is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc curve_p256_is_on_curve_affine with arena, ax, ay
End Process
